# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aav-vectors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Several features make AAV an attractive candidate for creating viral vectors for gene therapy, and for the creation of isogenic human disease models.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Gene therapy vectors using AAV can infect both dividing and quiescent cells and persist in an extrachromosomal state without integrating into the genome of the host cell.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In the native virus, however, integration of virally carried genes into the host genome does occur.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Integration can be important for certain applications, but can also have unwanted consequences.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Recent human clinical trials using AAV for gene therapy in the retina have shown promise.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In March 2023, a series of *Nature* papers detected high titres of adeno-associated virus 2 (AAV2), alongside adenovirus and herpesvirus, in samples from a wave of childhood hepatitis.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] One paper suggested that AAV2 co-infection may contribute to more serious liver disease than infection with only adeno- or herpesviruses and that the causal link remains to be established.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The adeno-associated virus (AAV), previously thought to be a contaminant in adenovirus preparations, was first identified as a dependoparvovirus in the 1960s in the laboratories of Bob Atchison at University of Pittsburgh and Wallace Rowe at the NIH.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Serological studies in humans subsequently indicated that, despite being present in people infected by helper viruses such as adenovirus or herpes virus, AAV itself did not cause any disease.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] At present, adeno-associated virus (AAV) vectors are considered the gold standard in gene therapy.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Wild-type AAV has attracted considerable interest from gene therapy researchers due to a number of features.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Chief amongst these was the virus's apparent lack of pathogenicity.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] It can also infect non-dividing cells and has the ability to stably integrate into the host cell genome at a specific site (designated AAVS1) in the human chromosome 19.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] This feature makes it somewhat more predictable than retroviruses, which present the threat of a random insertion and of mutagenesis, which is sometimes followed by development of a cancer.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The AAV genome integrates most frequently into the site mentioned, while random incorporations into the genome take place with a negligible frequency.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Development of AAVs as gene therapy vectors, however, has eliminated this integrative capacity by removal of the *rep* and *cap* from the DNA of the vector.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The desired gene together with a promoter to drive transcription of the gene is inserted between the inverted terminal repeats (ITRs) that aid in concatemer formation in the nucleus after the single-stranded vector DNA is converted by host cell DNA polymerase complexes into double-stranded DNA.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] AAV-based gene therapy vectors form episomal concatemers in the host cell nucleus.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In non-dividing cells, these concatemers remain intact for the life of the host cell.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In dividing cells, AAV DNA is lost through cell division, since the episomal DNA is not replicated along with the host cell DNA.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Random integration of AAV DNA into the host genome is detectable but occurs at very low frequency.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] AAVs also present very low immunogenicity, seemingly restricted to generation of neutralizing antibodies, while they induce no clearly defined cytotoxic response.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] This feature, along with the ability to infect quiescent cells present their dominance over adenoviruses as vectors for human gene therapy.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The primary method for AAV production involves transient transfection of HEK-293 cells using three plasmids that carry the therapeutic gene, AAV rep/cap genes, and helper adenoviral genes.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The production process includes cultivation, particularly in bioreactors, and purification aimed at increasing the yield of full capsids and removing impurities.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] To improve productivity, new methods are being developed, such as using engineered recombinant helper viruses and establishing stable producer cell lines.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Use of the virus does present some disadvantages.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The cloning capacity of the vector is relatively limited and most therapeutic genes require the complete replacement of the virus's 4.8 kilobase genome.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Large genes are, therefore, not suitable for use in a standard AAV vector.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Because of AAV's specialized gene therapy advantages, researchers have created an altered version of AAV termed self-complementary adeno-associated virus (scAAV).
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Whereas AAV packages a single strand of DNA and must wait for its second strand to be synthesized, scAAV packages two shorter strands that are complementary to each other.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] By avoiding second-strand synthesis, scAAV can express more quickly, although as a caveat, scAAV can only encode half of the already limited capacity of AAV.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Recent reports suggest that scAAV vectors are more immunogenic than single stranded adenovirus vectors, inducing a stronger activation of cytotoxic T lymphocytes.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Humoral immunity instigated by infection with the wild type is thought to be common.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The associated neutralising activity limits the usefulness of the most commonly used serotype AAV2 in certain applications.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Accordingly, the majority of clinical trials under way involve delivery of AAV2 into the brain, a relatively immunologically privileged organ.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In the brain, AAV2 is strongly neuron-specific.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] As of 2019, AAV vectors have been used in over 250 clinical trials worldwide, approximately 8.3% of virus-vectored gene-therapy trials.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Recently, promising results have been obtained from Phase 1 and Phase 2 trials for a number of diseases, including Leber's congenital amaurosis, hemophilia, congestive heart failure, spinal muscular atrophy, lipoprotein lipase deficiency, and Parkinson's disease.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] AAV based gene therapy products have entered the worldwide market following completion of successful clinical trials.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The table below contains FDA approved gene therapies that have entered the American Market and possibly other markets.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The AAV genome is built of single-stranded deoxyribonucleic acid (ssDNA), either positive- or negative-sensed, which is about 4.7 kilobase long.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The genome comprises ITRs at both ends of the DNA strand, and two open reading frames (ORFs): *rep* and *cap*.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The former is composed of four overlapping genes encoding Rep proteins required for the AAV life cycle, and the latter contains overlapping nucleotide sequences of capsid proteins: VP1, VP2 and VP3, which interact to form a capsid with icosahedral symmetry.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The inverted terminal repeat (ITR) sequences comprise 145 bases each.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] They were named so because of their symmetry, which was shown to be required for efficient multiplication of the AAV genome.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The feature of these sequences that gives them this property is their ability to form a hairpin, which contributes to so-called self-priming that allows primase-independent synthesis of the second DNA strand.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The ITRs were also shown to be required for both integration of the AAV DNA into the host cell genome (19th chromosome in humans) and rescue from it, as well as for efficient encapsidation of the AAV DNA combined with generation of a fully assembled, deoxyribonuclease-resistant AAV particles.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] With regard to gene therapy, ITRs seem to be the only sequences required *in cis* next to the therapeutic gene: structural (*cap*) and packaging (*rep*) proteins can be delivered *in trans*.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] With this assumption many methods were established for efficient production of recombinant AAV (rAAV) vectors containing a reporter or therapeutic gene.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] However, it was also published that the ITRs are not the only elements required *in cis* for the effective replication and encapsidation.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] A few research groups have identified a sequence designated *cis-acting Rep-dependent element* (CARE) inside the coding sequence of the *rep* gene.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] CARE was shown to augment the replication and encapsidation when present *in cis*.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] On the "left side" of the genome there are two promoters called p5 and p19, from which two overlapping messenger ribonucleic acids (mRNAs) of different length can be produced.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Each of these contains an intron which can be either spliced out or not.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Given these possibilities, four various mRNAs, and consequently four various Rep proteins with overlapping sequence can be synthesized.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Their names depict their sizes in kilodaltons (kDa): Rep78, Rep68, Rep52 and Rep40.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Rep78 and 68 can specifically bind the hairpin formed by the ITR in the self-priming act and cleave at a specific region, designated terminal resolution site, within the hairpin.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] They were also shown to be necessary for the AAVS1-specific integration of the AAV genome.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] All four Rep proteins were shown to bind ATP and to possess helicase activity.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] It was also shown that they upregulate the transcription from the p40 promoter (mentioned below), but downregulate both p5 and p19 promoters.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The right side of a positive-sensed AAV genome encodes overlapping sequences of three capsid proteins, VP1, VP2 and VP3, and two accessory proteins, MAAP & AAP, which start from one promoter, designated p40.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The molecular weights of these proteins are 87, 72 and 62 kiloDaltons, respectively.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The AAV capsid is composed of a mixture of VP1, VP2, and VP3 totaling 60 monomers arranged in icosahedral symmetry in a ratio of 1:1:10, with an empty mass of approximately 3.8 MDa.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The *cap* gene produces an additional, non-structural protein called the Assembly-Activating Protein (AAP).
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] This protein is produced from ORF2 and is essential for the capsid-assembly process.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The exact function of this protein in the assembly process and its structure have not been solved to date.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] All three VPs are translated from one mRNA.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] After this mRNA is synthesized, it can be spliced in two different manners: either a longer or shorter intron can be excised resulting in the formation of two pools of mRNAs: a 2.3 kb- and a 2.6 kb-long mRNA pool.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Usually, especially in the presence of adenovirus, the longer intron is preferred, so the 2.3-kb-long mRNA represents the so-called "major splice".
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In this form the first AUG codon, from which the synthesis of VP1 protein starts, is cut out, resulting in a reduced overall level of VP1 protein synthesis.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The first AUG codon that remains in the major splice is the initiation codon for VP3 protein.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] However, upstream of that codon in the same open reading frame lies an ACG sequence (encoding threonine) which is surrounded by an optimal Kozak context.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] This contributes to a low level of synthesis of VP2 protein, which is actually VP3 protein with additional N terminal residues, as is VP1.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Since the bigger intron is preferred to be spliced out, and since in the major splice the ACG codon is a much weaker translation initiation signal, the ratio at which the AAV structural proteins are synthesized *in vivo* is about 1:1:20, which is the same as in the mature virus particle.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The unique fragment at the N terminus of VP1 protein was shown to possess the phospholipase A2 (PLA2) activity, which is probably required for the releasing of AAV particles from late endosomes.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Muralidhar *et al.* reported that VP2 and VP3 are crucial for correct virion assembly.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] More recently, however, Warrington *et al.* showed VP2 to be unnecessary for the complete virus particle formation and an efficient infectivity, and also presented that VP2 can tolerate large insertions in its N terminus, while VP1 can not, probably because of the PLA2 domain presence.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] These PTMs differ depending on the manufacturing production platform.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Another such discovery is the fact that AAV genomes are epigenetically methylated during production.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Besides price, these findings might affect expression kinetics, rAAV receptor binding, trafficking, vector immunogenicity, and expression durability.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Two species of AAV were recognised by the International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses in 2013: *adeno-associated dependoparvovirus A* (formerly AAV-1, −2, −3 and −4) and *adeno-associated dependoparvovirus B* (formerly AAV-5).
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Until the 1990s, virtually all AAV biology was studied using AAV serotype 2.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] However, AAV is highly prevalent in humans and other primates and several serotypes have been isolated from various tissue samples.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Serotypes 2, 3, 5, and 6 were discovered in human cells, AAV serotypes 1, 4, and 7–11 in nonhuman primate samples.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] As of 2006 there have been 11 AAV serotypes described, the 11th in 2004.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] AAV capsid proteins contain 12 hypervariable surface regions, with most variability occurring in the threefold proximal peaks, but the parvovirus genome in general presents highly conserved replication and structural genes across serotypes.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] All of the known serotypes can infect cells from multiple diverse tissue types.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Serotype 2 (AAV2) has been the most extensively examined so far.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] AAV2 presents natural tropism towards skeletal muscles, neurons, vascular smooth muscle cells and hepatocytes.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Three cell receptors have been described for AAV2: heparan sulfate proteoglycan (HSPG), aVβ5 integrin and fibroblast growth factor receptor 1 (FGFR-1).
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The first functions as a primary receptor, while the latter two have a co-receptor activity and enable AAV to enter the cell by receptor-mediated endocytosis.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] These study results have been disputed by Qiu, Handa, *et al.* HSPG functions as the primary receptor, though its abundance in the extracellular matrix can scavenge AAV particles and impair the infection efficiency.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Studies have shown that serotype 2 of the virus (AAV-2) apparently kills cancer cells without harming healthy ones.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] This could lead to a new anti-cancer agent.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In March 2023, a series of *Nature* papers linked infection of adeno-associated virus 2 (AAV2) to a wave of childhood hepatitis.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Although AAV2 is the most popular serotype in various AAV-based research, it has been shown that other serotypes can be more effective as gene delivery vectors.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In the brain, most AAV serotypes show neuronal tropism, while AAV5 also transduces astrocytes.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] AAV6, a hybrid of AAV1 and AAV2, also shows lower immunogenicity than AAV2.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Serotypes can differ with the respect to the receptors they are bound to.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] For example, AAV4 and AAV5 transduction can be inhibited by soluble sialic acids (of different form for each of these serotypes), and AAV5 was shown to enter cells via the platelet-derived growth factor receptor.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] There have been many efforts to engineer and improve new AAV variants for both clinical and research purposes.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Such modifications include new tropisms to target specific tissues, and modified surface residues to evade detection by the immune system.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Beyond opting for particular strains of recombinant AAV (rAAV) to target particular cells, researchers have also explored AAV pseudotyping, the practice of creating hybrids of certain AAV strains to approach an even more refined target.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The hybrid is created by taking a capsid from one strain and the genome from another strain.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Other efforts to engineer and improve new AAV variants have involved the ancestral reconstruction of virus variants to generate new vectors with enhanced properties for clinical applications and the study of AAV biology.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Tags may be inserted into the AAV capsid to allow coupling of binders and improve targeting to specific cell-types or tissues.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] AAV is of particular interest to gene therapists due to its apparent limited capacity to induce immune responses in humans, a factor which should positively influence vector transduction efficiency while reducing the risk of any immune-associated pathology.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] AAV is not considered to have any known role in disease.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] However, host immune system response and immune tolerance reduce the efficacy of AAV-mediated gene therapy.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Host immune response has been shown to respond to the AAV vectors, the transduced cells, and the transduced proteins.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The immune response can be subdivided into two categories: innate and adaptive, the latter of which is divided into humoral and cell-mediated.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The innate immune response to the AAV vectors has been characterised in animal models.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Intravenous administration in mice causes transient production of pro-inflammatory cytokines and some infiltration of neutrophils and other leukocytes into the liver, which seems to sequester a large percentage of the injected viral particles.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Both soluble factor levels and cell infiltration appear to return to baseline within six hours.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] By contrast, more aggressive viruses produce innate responses lasting 24 hours or longer.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In-vivo studies indicate that AAV vectors interact with the Toll-like receptor (TLR)9- and TLR2-MyD88 pathways to trigger the innate immune response by stimulating the production of interferons.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Due to previous natural infection, many people have preexisting neutralizing antibodies (NAbs) against AAV's, which can significantly hinder its application in gene therapy.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Even though AAV's are highly variable among wild-type and synthetic variants, antibody recognition sites may be conserved evolutionarily.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The virus is known to instigate robust humoral immunity in animal models and in the human population, where up to 80% of individuals are thought to be seropositive for AAV2.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Antibodies are known to be neutralising, and for gene therapy applications these do impact vector transduction efficiency via some routes of administration.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] As well as persistent AAV specific antibody levels, it appears from both prime-boost studies in animals and from clinical trials that the B-cell memory is also strong.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In seropositive humans, circulating IgG antibodies for AAV2 appear to be primarily composed of the IgG1 and IgG2 subclasses, with little or no IgG3 or IgG4 present.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The cell-mediated response to the virus and to vectors is poorly characterised, and has been largely ignored in the literature as recently as 2005.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Clinical trials using an AAV2-based vector to treat haemophilia B seem to indicate that targeted destruction of transduced cells may be occurring.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Combined with data that shows that CD8+ T-cells can recognise elements of the AAV capsid *in vitro*, it appears that there may be a cytotoxic T lymphocyte response to AAV vectors.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Cytotoxic responses would imply the involvement of CD4+ T helper cells in the response to AAV and *in vitro* data from human studies suggests that the virus may indeed induce such responses, including both Th1 and Th2 memory responses.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] A number of candidate T cell stimulating epitopes have been identified within the AAV capsid protein VP1, which may be attractive targets for modification of the capsid if the virus is to be used as a vector for gene therapy.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Some of these steps may look different in various types of cells, which, in part, contributes to the defined and quite limited native tropism of AAV.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Replication of the virus can also vary in one cell type, depending on the cell's current cell cycle phase.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The characteristic feature of the adeno-associated virus is a deficiency in replication and thus its inability to multiply in unaffected cells.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Adeno-associated virus spreads by co-infecting a cell with a helper virus.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The first helper virus that was described as providing successful generation of new AAV particles, was the adenovirus, from which the AAV name originated.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] It was then shown that AAV replication can be facilitated by selected proteins derived from the adenovirus genome, by other viruses such as HSV or vaccinia, or by genotoxic agents, such as UV irradiation or hydroxyurea.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] Depending on the presence or absence of a helper virus, the life cycle of AAV follows either a lytic or lysogenic pathway, respectively.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] If there is a helper virus, AAV's gene expression activates, allowing the virus to replicate using the host cell's polymerase.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] When the helper virus kills the host cell, the new AAV virions are released.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] If there is not a helper virus present, AAV exhibits lysogenic behavior.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] When AAV infects a cell alone, its gene expression is repressed (AAV does not replicate), and its genome is incorporated into the host genome (into human chromosome 19).
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In rare cases, lysis can occur without a helper virus, but usually AAV cannot replicate and kill a cell on its own.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] The minimal set of the adenoviral genes required for efficient generation, of progeny AAV particles, was discovered by Matsushita, Ellinger *et al.* This discovery allowed for new production methods of recombinant AAV, which do not require adenoviral co-infection of the AAV-producing cells.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In the absence of helper virus or genotoxic factors, AAV DNA can either integrate into the host genome or persist in episomal form.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In the former case integration is mediated by Rep78 and Rep68 proteins and requires the presence of ITRs flanking the region being integrated.
[src:aav-vectors/adeno-associated-virus] In mice, the AAV genome has been observed persisting for long periods of time in quiescent tissues, such as skeletal muscles, in episomal form (a circular head-to-tail conformation).
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] A **capsid** is the protein shell of a virus, enclosing its genetic material.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] It consists of several oligomeric (repeating) structural subunits made of protein called protomers.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The observable 3-dimensional morphological subunits, which may or may not correspond to individual proteins, are called capsomeres.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The proteins making up the capsid are called **capsid proteins** or **viral coat proteins** (**VCP**).
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The virus genomic component inside the capsid, along with occasionally present virus core protein, is called the **virus core**.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The capsid and core together are referred to as a **nucleocapsid** (cf. also virion).
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Capsids are broadly classified according to their structure.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The majority of the viruses have capsids with either helical or icosahedral structure.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Some viruses, such as bacteriophages, have developed more complicated structures due to constraints of elasticity and electrostatics.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The icosahedral shape, which has 20 equilateral triangular faces, approximates a sphere, while the helical shape resembles the shape of a spring, taking the space of a cylinder but not being a cylinder itself.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The capsid faces may consist of one or more proteins.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] For example, the foot-and-mouth disease virus capsid has faces consisting of three proteins named VP1–3.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Some viruses are *enveloped*, meaning that the capsid is coated with a lipid membrane known as the viral envelope.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The envelope is acquired by the capsid from an intracellular membrane in the virus' host; examples include the inner nuclear membrane, the Golgi membrane, and the cell's outer membrane.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Once the virus has infected a cell and begins replicating itself, new capsid subunits are synthesized using the protein biosynthesis mechanism of the cell.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] In some viruses, including those with helical capsids and especially those with RNA genomes, the capsid proteins co-assemble with their genomes.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] In other viruses, especially more complex viruses with double-stranded DNA genomes, the capsid proteins assemble into empty precursor **procapsids** that include a specialized portal structure at one vertex.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Through this portal, viral DNA is translocated into the capsid.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Structural analyses of major capsid protein (MCP) architectures have been used to categorise viruses into lineages.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] For example, the bacteriophage PRD1, the algal virus *Paramecium bursaria Chlorella virus-1* (PBCV-1), mimivirus and the mammalian adenovirus have been placed in the same lineage, whereas tailed, double-stranded DNA bacteriophages (*Caudovirales*) and herpesvirus belong to a second lineage.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The icosahedral structure is extremely common among viruses.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The icosahedron consists of 20 triangular faces delimited by 12 fivefold vertexes and consists of 60 asymmetric units.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Thus, an icosahedral virus is made of 60N protein subunits.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The number and arrangement of capsomeres in an icosahedral capsid can be classified using the "quasi-equivalence principle" proposed by Donald Caspar and Aaron Klug.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Like the Goldberg polyhedra, an icosahedral structure can be regarded as being constructed from pentamers and hexamers.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The structures can be indexed by two integers *h* and *k*, with $h\geq 1$ and $k\geq 0$ ; the structure can be thought of as taking *h* steps from the edge of a pentamer, turning 60 degrees counterclockwise, then taking *k* steps to get to the next pentamer.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] In this scheme, icosahedral capsids contain 12 pentamers plus 10(*T* − 1) hexamers.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The *T*-number is representative of the size and complexity of the capsids.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Geometric examples for many values of *h*, *k*, and *T* can be found at List of geodesic polyhedra and Goldberg polyhedra.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Many exceptions to this rule exist: For example, the polyomaviruses and papillomaviruses have pentamers instead of hexamers in hexavalent positions on a quasi T = 7 lattice.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Members of the double-stranded RNA virus lineage, including reovirus, rotavirus and bacteriophage φ6 have capsids built of 120 copies of capsid protein, corresponding to a T = 2 capsid, or arguably a T = 1 capsid with a dimer in the asymmetric unit.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] An elongated icosahedron is a common shape for the heads of bacteriophages.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Such a structure is composed of a cylinder with a cap at either end.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The cylinder is composed of 10 elongated triangular faces.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The Q number (or Tmid), which can be any positive integer, specifies the number of triangles, composed of asymmetric subunits, that make up the 10 triangles of the cylinder.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The caps are classified by the T (or Tend) number.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The bacterium *E. coli* is the host for bacteriophage T4 that has a prolate head structure.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The bacteriophage encoded gp31 protein appears to be functionally homologous to *E. coli* chaperone protein GroES and able to substitute for it in the assembly of bacteriophage T4 virions during infection.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Like GroES, gp31 forms a stable complex with GroEL chaperonin that is absolutely necessary for the folding and assembly *in vivo* of the bacteriophage T4 major capsid protein gp23.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Many rod-shaped and filamentous plant viruses have capsids with helical symmetry.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The helical structure can be described as a set of *n* 1-D molecular helices related by an *n*-fold axial symmetry.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The helical transformation are classified into two categories: one-dimensional and two-dimensional helical systems.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Creating an entire helical structure relies on a set of translational and rotational matrices which are coded in the protein data bank.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Helical symmetry is given by the formula *P* = *μ* x *ρ*, where *μ* is the number of structural units per turn of the helix, *ρ* is the axial rise per unit and *P* is the pitch of the helix.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The structure is said to be open due to the characteristic that any volume can be enclosed by varying the length of the helix.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The most understood helical virus is the tobacco mosaic virus.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The virus is a single molecule of (+) strand RNA.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Each coat protein on the interior of the helix binds three nucleotides of the RNA genome, with the overall polymer having a μ value of 16.33 protein subunits per helical turn.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Influenza A viruses differ by comprising multiple ribonucleoproteins which organize the segmented RNA into double helical structures.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The virus must assemble a stable, protective protein shell to protect the genome from lethal chemical and physical agents.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] These include extremes of pH or temperature and proteolytic and nucleolytic enzymes.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] For non-enveloped viruses, the capsid itself may be involved in interaction with receptors on the host cell, leading to penetration of the host cell membrane and internalization of the capsid.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] Delivery of the genome occurs by subsequent uncoating or disassembly of the capsid and release of the genome into the cytoplasm, or by ejection of the genome through a specialized portal structure directly into the host cell nucleus.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] It has been suggested that many viral capsid proteins have evolved on multiple occasions from functionally diverse cellular proteins.
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] As a result, some capsid proteins are widespread in viruses infecting distantly related organisms (e.g., capsid proteins with the jelly-roll fold), whereas others are restricted to a particular group of viruses (e.g., capsid proteins of alphaviruses).
[src:aav-vectors/capsid] The displacement of these ancestral genes between cellular organisms could favor the appearance of new viruses during evolution.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] The name refers to the fact that all dependoviruses, except duck parvovirus and goose parvovirus, cannot replicate productively in their host cell without the cell being coinfected by a helper virus such as an adenovirus, a herpesvirus, or a vaccinia virus.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] Dependoparvoviruses have an icosahedral shape, measure 22 nm and are composed of 60 wedge-shaped proteins (triangulation number = 1).
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] Three proteins (VP1, VP2 and VP3) are present in each capsomere.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] Each capsid is made from 5 VP1, 5 VP2, and 50 VP3 proteins.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] The genome is a single molecule of single stranded DNA with a length of 4.7 kilobases.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] The 3' open reading frame is the structural capsid protein, cap, which can be spliced to form two RNAs, one for virion protein 1 (VP1) and the other goes on to eventually make VP2 and VP3.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] The second gene, rep, can be spliced into four different, nonstructural, regulatory proteins that all aid in the genome replication.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] These proteins are named Rep 78, Rep68, Rep 52, and Rep 40 based on their molecular weight.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] Due to inverted terminal repeats (ITRs) at each end of the genome, a T-shaped secondary structure is formed.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] The complementary areas leave a 3' hydroxyl group single stranded for the replication to begin.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] This 3' hydroxyl group is used as a primer for the leading strand synthesis.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] Both positive and negative sense strands of DNA are made.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] Double stranded intermediates are formed throughout the replication; this means the two strands, positive and negative sense, will be matched up.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] These viruses are capable of replication within all vertebrates.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] They are only limited by the virus they must infect with, also known as the helper virus.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] These helper viruses are necessary for the replication of a dependoparvovirus.
[src:aav-vectors/dependoparvovirus] Helper viruses include adenoviruses and herpesviruses.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] An **episome** is a special type of plasmid, which remains as a part of the eukaryotic genome without integration.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] Episomes manage this by replicating together with the rest of the genome and subsequently associating with metaphase chromosomes during mitosis.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] Episomes do not degrade, unlike standard plasmids, and can be designed so that they are not epigenetically silenced inside the eukaryotic cell nucleus.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] Episomes can be observed in nature in certain types of long-term infection by adeno-associated virus or Epstein-Barr virus.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] In 2004, it was proposed that non-viral episomes might be used in genetic therapy for long-term change in gene expression.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] As of 1999, there were many known sequences of DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) that allow a standard plasmid to become episomally retained.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] The length of episomal retention is fairly variable between different genetic constructs and there are many known features in the sequence of an episome which will affect the length and stability of genetic expression of the carried transgene.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] Among these features is the number of CpG sites which contribute to epigenetic silencing of the transgene carried by the episome.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] The mechanism behind episomal retention in the case of S/MAR episomes is still uncertain.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] As of 1985, in the case of latent Epstein-Barr virus infection, episomes seemed to be associated with nuclear proteins of the host cell through a set of viral proteins.
[src:aav-vectors/episome] Episomes in prokaryotes are special sequences which can divide either separate from or integrated into the prokaryotic chromosome.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] An **inverted repeat** (or **IR**) is a single stranded sequence of nucleotides followed downstream by its reverse complement.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The intervening sequence of nucleotides between the initial sequence and the reverse complement can be any length including zero.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] For example, 5'---TTACGnnnnnnCGTAA---3' is an inverted repeat sequence.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] When the intervening length is zero, the composite sequence is a palindromic sequence.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Both inverted repeats and direct repeats constitute types of nucleotide sequences that occur repetitively.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] These repeated DNA sequences often range from a pair of nucleotides to a whole gene, while the proximity of the repeat sequences varies between widely dispersed and simple tandem arrays.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The short tandem repeat sequences may exist as just a few copies in a small region to thousands of copies dispersed all over the genome of most eukaryotes.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Repeat sequences with about 10–100 base pairs are known as minisatellites, while shorter repeat sequences having mostly 2–4 base pairs are known as microsatellites.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The most common repeats include the dinucleotide repeats, which have the bases AC on one DNA strand, and GT on the complementary strand.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Some elements of the genome with unique sequences function as exons, introns and regulatory DNA.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Though the most familiar loci of the repetitive sequences are the centromere and the telomere, a large portion of the repeated sequences in the genome are found among the noncoding DNA.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Inverted repeats have a number of important biological functions.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] They define the boundaries in transposons and indicate regions capable of self-complementary base pairing (regions within a single sequence which can base pair with each other).
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] These properties play an important role in genome instability and contribute not only to cellular evolution and genetic diversity but also to mutation and disease.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] In order to study these effects in detail, a number of programs and databases have been developed to assist in discovery and annotation of inverted repeats in various genomes.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] "nnnnnn" represents any number of intervening nucleotides.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] A direct repeat occurs when a sequence is repeated with the same pattern downstream.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] There is no inversion and no reverse complement associated with a direct repeat.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The nucleotide sequence written in bold characters signifies the repeated sequence.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] It may or may not have intervening nucleotides.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Linguistically, a typical direct repeat is comparable to rhyming, as in "t**ime** on a d**ime**".
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] A direct repeat with *no* intervening nucleotides between the initial sequence and its downstream copy is a Tandem repeat.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Linguistically, a typical tandem repeat is comparable to stuttering, or deliberately repeated words, as in "bye-bye".
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] An inverted repeat sequence with *no* intervening nucleotides between the initial sequence and its downstream reverse complement is a palindrome.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] EXAMPLE: Step 1: start with an inverted repeat: 5' TTACGnnnnnnCGTAA 3' Step 2: remove intervening nucleotides: 5' TTACGCGTAA 3' This resulting sequence is palindromic because it is the reverse complement of itself.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] This is the same as the test sequence above, and thus, it is a palindrome.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The diverse genome-wide repeats are derived from transposable elements, which are now understood to "jump" about different genomic locations, without transferring their original copies.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Subsequent shuttling of the same sequences over numerous generations ensures their multiplicity throughout the genome.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The limited recombination of the sequences between two distinct sequence elements known as conservative site-specific recombination (CSSR) results in inversions of the DNA segment, based on the arrangement of the recombination recognition sequences on the donor DNA and recipient DNA.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Again, the orientation of two of the recombining sites within the donor DNA molecule relative to the asymmetry of the intervening DNA cleavage sequences, known as the crossover region, is pivotal to the formation of either inverted repeats or direct repeats.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Thus, recombination occurring at a pair of inverted sites will invert the DNA sequence between the two sites.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Very stable chromosomes have been observed with comparatively fewer numbers of inverted repeats than direct repeats, suggesting a relationship between chromosome stability and the number of repeats.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Terminal inverted repeats have been observed in the DNA of various eukaryotic transposons, even though their source remains unknown.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Inverted repeats are principally found at the origins of replication of cell organism and organelles that range from phage plasmids, mitochondria, and eukaryotic viruses to mammalian cells.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The replication origins of the phage G4 and other related phages comprise a segment of nearly 139 nucleotide bases that include three inverted repeats that are essential for replication priming.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] To a large extent, portions of nucleotide repeats are quite often observed as part of rare DNA combinations.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The others could be described as long inverted repeats having the tendency to produce hairpins and cruciform, and finally direct tandem repeats, which commonly exist in structures described as slipped-loop, cruciform and left-handed Z-DNA.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Past studies suggest that repeats are a common feature of eukaryotes unlike the prokaryotes and archaea.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Other reports suggest that irrespective of the comparative shortage of repeat elements in prokaryotic genomes, they nevertheless contain hundreds or even thousands of large repeats.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Current genomic analysis seem to suggest the existence of a large excess of perfect inverted repeats in many prokaryotic genomes as compared to eukaryotic genomes.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Pseudoknots are common structural motifs found in RNA.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] They are formed by two nested stem-loops such that the stem of one structure is formed from the loop of the other.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] There are multiple folding topologies among pseudoknots and great variation in loop lengths, making them a structurally diverse group.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Inverted repeats are a key component of pseudoknots as can be seen in the illustration of a naturally occurring pseudoknot found in the human telomerase RNA component.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Four different sets of inverted repeats are involved in this structure.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Sets 1 and 2 are the stem of stem-loop A and are part of the loop for stem-loop B.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Similarly, sets 3 and 4 are the stem for stem-loop B and are part of the loop for stem-loop A.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Pseudoknots play a number of different roles in biology.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The telomerase pseudoknot in the illustration is critical to that enzyme's activity.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The ribozyme for the *hepatitis delta virus (HDV)* folds into a double-pseudoknot structure and self-cleaves its circular genome to produce a single-genome-length RNA.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Pseudoknots also play a role in programmed ribosomal frameshifting found in some viruses and required in the replication of retroviruses.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Inverted repeats play an important role in riboswitches, which are RNA regulatory elements that control the expression of genes that produce the mRNA, of which they are part.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] A simplified example of the flavin mononucleotide (FMN) riboswitch is shown in the illustration.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] This riboswitch exists in the mRNA transcript and has several stem-loop structures upstream from the coding region.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] However, only the key stem-loops are shown in the illustration, which has been greatly simplified to help show the role of the inverted repeats.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] There are multiple inverted repeats in this riboswitch as indicated in green (yellow background) and blue (orange background).
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] In the absence of FMN, the Anti-termination structure is the preferred conformation for the mRNA transcript.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] It is created by base-pairing of the inverted repeat region circled in red.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] When FMN is present, it may bind to the loop and prevent formation of the Anti-termination structure.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] This allows two different sets of inverted repeats to base-pair and form the Termination structure.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The stem-loop on the 3' end is a transcriptional terminator because the sequence immediately following it is a string of uracils (U).
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] If this stem-loop forms (due to the presence of FMN) as the growing RNA strand emerges from the RNA polymerase complex, it will create enough structural tension to cause the RNA strand to dissociate and thus terminate transcription.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The dissociation occurs easily because the base-pairing between the U's in the RNA and the A's in the template strand are the weakest of all base-pairings.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Thus, at higher concentration levels, FMN down-regulates its own transcription by increasing the formation of the termination structure.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Inverted repeats are often described as "hotspots" of eukaryotic and prokaryotic genomic instability.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Long inverted repeats are deemed to greatly influence the stability of the genome of various organisms.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] This is exemplified in *E. coli*, where genomic sequences with long inverted repeats are seldom replicated, but rather deleted with rapidity.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Again, the long inverted repeats observed in yeast greatly favor recombination within the same and adjacent chromosomes, resulting in an equally very high rate of deletion.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Finally, a very high rate of deletion and recombination were also observed in mammalian chromosomes regions with inverted repeats.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Reported differences in the stability of genomes of interrelated organisms are always an indication of a disparity in inverted repeats.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The instability results from the tendency of inverted repeats to fold into hairpin- or cruciform-like DNA structures.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] These special structures can hinder or confuse DNA replication and other genomic activities.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Thus, inverted repeats lead to special configurations in both RNA and DNA that can ultimately cause mutations and disease.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The illustration shows an inverted repeat undergoing cruciform extrusion.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] DNA in the region of the inverted repeat unwinds and then recombines, forming a four-way junction with two stem-loop structures.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The cruciform structure occurs because the inverted repeat sequences self-pair to each other on their own strand.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Extruded cruciforms can lead to frameshift mutations when a DNA sequence has inverted repeats in the form of a palindrome combined with regions of direct repeats on either side.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] During transcription, slippage and partial dissociation of the polymerase from the template strand can lead to both deletion and insertion mutations.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Deletion occurs when a portion of the unwound template strand forms a stem-loop that gets "skipped" by the transcription machinery.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Insertion occurs when a stem-loop forms in a dissociated portion of the nascent (newly synthesized) strand causing a portion of the template strand to be transcribed twice.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Imperfect inverted repeats can lead to mutations through intrastrand and interstrand switching.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The antithrombin III gene's coding region is an example of an imperfect inverted repeat as shown in the figure on the right.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The stem-loop structure forms with a bump at the bottom because the G and T do not pair up.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] A strand switch event could result in the G (in the bump) being replaced by an A which removes the "imperfection" in the inverted repeat and provides a stronger stem-loop structure.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] However, the replacement also creates a point mutation converting the GCA codon to ACA.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] If the strand switch event is followed by a second round of DNA replication, the mutation may become fixed in the genome and lead to disease.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Specifically, the missense mutation would lead to a defective gene and a deficiency in antithrombin which could result in the development of venous thromboembolism (blood clots within a vein).
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] Mutations in the collagen gene can lead to the disease Osteogenesis Imperfecta, which is characterized by brittle bones.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] In the illustration, a stem-loop formed from an imperfect inverted repeat is mutated with a thymine (T) nucleotide insertion as a result of an inter- or intrastrand switch.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] The addition of the T creates a base-pairing "match up" with the adenine (A) that was previously a "bump" on the left side of the stem.
[src:aav-vectors/inverted-repeat] While this addition makes the stem stronger and perfects the inverted repeat, it also creates a frameshift mutation in the nucleotide sequence which alters the reading frame and will result in an incorrect expression of the gene.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] Some bacteria and viruses have a broad tissue tropism and can infect many types of cells and tissues.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] Other viruses may infect primarily a single tissue.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] For example, rabies virus affects primarily neuronal tissue.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] Similarly, JC virus (JCV) primarily affects and resides in kidneys.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] The cellular receptors are the proteins found on a cell or viral surface.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] These receptors are like keys, allowing the viral cell to fuse with or attach itself to a cell.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] The way that these proteins are acquired is through a similar process to that of an infection cycle.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] Example: HIV has a gp120, which is precisely what the CD4 marker is on the surface of the macrophages and T cells.
[src:aav-vectors/viral-tropism] Thus HIV can enter T cells and macrophages.
